$interpreted: Juan Yun: It's been a month since I've seen you—how are you holding up? How's Alliance lodging for the contestants? Seem's like...
Juan Yun: Uh, Princess, I wasn't done talking...!
Juan Yun: Princess, wait for me!
Juan Yun: Am I... too naive?
Tindoiimu: ...Yes.
Juan Yun: Wow, very straightforward...
Tindoiimu: Just tell me why you're trying to help me.
Tindoiimu: You already know I want to cut down the Udumbara and destroy the Alliance!
Tindoiimu: If you think doing me a few favors will make me give up on that goal, then—
Juan Yun: —I want you to join the tournament, and win.
Tindoiimu: You want me as your arbiter!?
Juan Yun: Apologies, but this is the only way I can think of that will keep you safe for good.
Juan Yun: I love my home, and would never put it in danger for you, but... can't I have you as my second priority?
Tindoiimu: ......
Tindoiimu: ...I was wrong. You're not naive—you're a joke.
Juan Yun: Ah...
Tindoiimu: You won't endanger your home!? The first thing I'll do if I become arbiter is chop down the Udumbara!
Tindoiimu: So you beasts can't rely on it anymore! Can't shamelessly massacre the Insect Tribe!
Juan Yun: ......
Juan Yun: ...You... won't do it...
Tindoiimu: Excuse me!?
Juan Yun: ...You were born to the Insect Tribe, but grew up in the Alliance. Love it or hate it... both places are home.
Juan Yun: You wouldn't turn your back on your home.
Juan Yun: ...We're similar, in that way.
Tindoiimu: ......
Tindoiimu: ...We're not similar in any way, qilin lord.
Tindoiimu: Not before, not later, not ever!
Juan Yun: ...!
Tindoiimu: The Alliance and the Insect Tribe cannot coexist—one thrives, the other dies.
Juan Yun: Princess! I truly want to help you! What can I do to make you believe me...
Juan Yun: Oh yeah! Tingko and Jihasaha!
Juan Yun: After they escaped, the Alliance shut off all exits. The two of them must still be trapped within Alliance borders, right?
Juan Yun: It's dangerous for them, the longer they stay there. What if I helped them get back to insect territory?
Tindoiimu: Your words mean nothing. They're well hidden. For all I know you're trying to lure them out!
Juan Yun: It's not like that! If you don't believe me, then poison me! If I betray you, don't give me the antidote!
Tindoiimu: Poison you!? The Udumbara cures all toxins, doesn't it? Poison won't do anything...
Tindoiimu: ...Unless...
Juan Yun: Unless?
Tindoiimu: Host my butterfly, temporarily.
Tindoiimu: If you break your promise, it'll take a bite out of your heart.
Juan Yun: ...I'll... die?
Tindoiimu: That's not all. Its life is bound to mine. If I die, it dies too.
Tindoiimu: And take the lives of my enemies with it.
Juan Yun: So if something happens to you, then it's game over for me?
Tindoiimu: That's right. If you're host to my butterfly, then our lives are bound.
Juan Yun: ......
Tindoiimu: See, I knew you would never sa—
Juan Yun: Let's do it. It's a good idea.
Tindoiimu: Are you serious!?
Juan Yun: I couldn't be any more serious.
Tindoiimu: Aren't you worried I could betray you?
Juan Yun: It's a large undertaking, raising one of your insects. It takes an incredible amount of energy, and time. Losing one would be devastating.
Juan Yun: So much so, that I bet you're bluffing. You wouldn't really let me host it.
Tindoiimu: You sure? A butterfly in exchange for the qilin lord? I think most people would see that as a pretty good deal.
Juan Yun: Well, I guess I'm not most people. I understand you.
Tindoiimu: ......
Tindoiimu: ......
Tindoiimu: Prepare yourself. This is going to hurt more than any poison.
Tindoiimu: We've been pairing with insects for generations, and still the first time is excruciatingly painful. I can't imagine how it'll feel for you.
Juan Yun: Well good. If I go through such pain, then you will have even more reason to trust me.
Tindoiimu: You're really... too naive.
